With Bitcoin, all network nodes are at the same time keepers of the account book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose another address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of data related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double encryption system.
In this way the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
With the content of the file it is also possible to ensure that the traded Bitcoins are available in the public accounts accounts spread throughout the network.
The crucial step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This happens through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, adding this additional line to the winner, who is a kind of preliminary central banker who has privilege.
It is a piece of the file, i.e. converting a large file into a shorter and clear electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that produces a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can hardly check if it is the right one.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wishes to pay two times very fast (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain without link, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer who solved the task gets 50 bitcoins.
