The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of activity, his work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskkie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society is made in 1954 in the November edition of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for a space company.
At the time there were already the first satellite technology projects, and it was not possible to see that the research of the space would have the future.
At its beginning in 1956, the Polish Space Society PTA tried to join the International Space Federation, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a regular member in autumn of 1956.
In the following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), Vice-President of the International Federation for Space.
He had the office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has participated in the development of the extremely successful meteorological rockets (Rakieta Meteorologicczna), the first Polish Rakete for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first start took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not completely 5 kg.
Later, a improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in 1959 the Błłdów desert began flight tests with the two-level RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another level of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the Rakete RM-34 should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used for monitoring high winds.
However, in 1962 the further development was stopped.
Following the first missiles of type RM, the Meteor-1 rocket was developed in the years 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-level rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the start weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) of these rockets were developed, different from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space with 0.4 litres of capacity, Meteor-1B over 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight height was 37 km for all three types.
In the years 1965 to 1968, the Meteor 2 rockets were developed in the Aerospace Institute, whose first flight tests started in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a 10 kg load to a height of about 60 km.
Then the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also important to mention Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which followed two years later the establishment of a national COSPAR Committee.
